observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) with the assistance of the Municipal Accountant to properly classify the expenditures in the LDRRMFIP based on the nature of the expenditures;


Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to incorporate in the AIP the list of projects and activities charged against the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years in accordance with Item 6.5 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1;

Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (ii) COA Circular No. 2015-009 in the proper recording of transactions in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS); and (iii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for proper documentation of transactions;   

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and its Secretariat to indicate the delivery/contract period in the PhilGEPS postings of Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed; and 



Municipal Engineer to require the contractors to submit pictures on embedded items and properly label the pictures as before, during and after construction with description of the items of work.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor and Municipal Budget Officer be guided by Section 336 of Republic Act No. 7160 and the provisions in the Budget Operations Manual for Local Government Units in the augmentation of funds;

Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator make sure that the list of programs, projects and activities identified are properly included/incorporated in the Investment Program/Plan;


BAC and its members be guided by the provision of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services and be always abreast with the issuances of the GPPB so that various requirements thereto are always complied with; and




Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 in the documentation of transactions; (ii) properly record/account donations (cash or in-kind) received by the Municipality in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002; and (iii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the procurement, issuance and inventory of goods and property, plant and equipment procured by the Municipality including those acquired through donations either in cash or in-kind.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to

(a) create an Inventory Committee to undertake the conduct of physical inventory of PPE owned by the Municipality and prepare the RPCPPE for reconciliation with the MAO records; 

(b) require the MA and GSO Officer to maintain the appropriate property records such as SLCs and PCs, respectively; 

(c) require the MA to provide the necessary allowance for depreciation on all depreciable assets of the Municipality; and

(d) instruct the MTO Officer to facilitate the transfer of ownership of the TCT on parcel of land purchased in CY 2019 under the name of the Municipality.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) with the assistance of the Municipal Accountant to properly classify the expenditures in the LDRRMFIP based on the nature of the expenditures;
Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to incorporate in the AIP the list of projects and activities charged against the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years in accordance with Item 6.5 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1;
Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (ii) COA Circular No. 2015-009 in the proper recording of transactions in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS); and (iii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for proper documentation of transactions;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and its Secretariat to indicate the delivery/contract period in the PhilGEPS postings of Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed; and
Municipal Engineer to require the contractors to submit pictures on embedded items and properly label the pictures as before, during and after construction with description of the items of work.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor and Municipal Budget Officer be guided by Section 336 of Republic Act No. 7160 and the provisions in the Budget Operations Manual for Local Government Units in the augmentation of funds;
Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator make sure that the list of programs, projects and activities identified are properly included/incorporated in the Investment Program/Plan;
BAC and its members be guided by the provision of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services and be always abreast with the issuances of the GPPB so that various requirements thereto are always complied with; and
Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 in the documentation of transactions; (ii) properly record/account donations (cash or in-kind) received by the Municipality in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002; and (iii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the procurement, issuance and inventory of goods and property, plant and equipment procured by the Municipality including those acquired through donations either in cash or in-kind.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Inventory Committee to conduct physical count for all the property owned by the Municipality and submit the Report on the Physical Count of PPE within the reglementary period as required under Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
b. Municipal General Services Officer to reconcile the physical inventory report with the PPE ledger cards of the Municipal Accounting Office;
c. OIC-Municipal Accountant to update the PPELCs and PCs and provide the complete and necessary information in both records; and
d. OIC-Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct PPE account balance in the Statement of Financial Position.

observations.managementAction:
The following actions were done:

Information Education Campaign (IEC) thru house to house campaign and conduct of assemblies to inform constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and the importance of their participation in the implementation of various SWM programs were done by the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) and even at the barangay level;

The Materials Recovery Facilities (MRF) of barangays were already functional and non-biodegradable wastes and special wastes were stored in this facility for further hauling of the Municipality to the municipal MRF;

Two MRFs funded by the transferred fund from the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) were established in Barangays Concepcion Sur and Concepcion Norte as additional facilities in the existing MRF of the Municipality;

Imposition of penalties to various ordinances including those related to solid waste management thru the issuance of citation tickets was already brought to the attention of the Sangguniang Bayan for the proper issuance of resolution or ordinance;

In March 2019, lot intended for Sanitary Landfill was purchased;

The open dumpsite was already closed/rehabilitated;

The Barangays regularly conduct synchronized clean-up drive through the Liga ng mga Barangay and MLGOO; and

Conducted a training workshop for all barangays officials and employees for the formulation of Barangay DRRM Plan and Solid Waste Management Plan and Waste Segregation Strategies and Implementation.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:

The LGU GFPS Technical Working Group (TWG) submit the GPB to the PPDO to ensure the alignment of the GAD PPAs to the priorities of the province and DILG Provincial Office for review and endorsement in accordance with the schedule to be observed in GAD Planning and Budgeting as provided under Section 4.0 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 amending Section C.5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

The GAD focal person ensure that the total amount reflected in the GPB corresponds to the total amount allocated for GAD in the Annual Budget of the Municipality;

The LGU GFPS accomplish the GMEF Organizational Assessment Questionnaire on the four (4) entry points of gender mainstreaming to acquire a holistic view of the gender mainstreaming process of the Municipality so that improvements, if any, may be made; and

The Municipal Mayor require the GAD focal person to ensure that GAD PPAs identified in the DILG-endorsed GAD Plan and Budget are implemented.

observations.managementAction:
1. The municipality had submitted an approved Solid Waste Management Plan covering the period of 2013-2022.
2. through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents through Information Education Campaign (IEC) on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and the importance of their participation in the implementation of various SWM programs;
3. through SWMB, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels on the designated garbage collection area and other public places and collect only those wastes which are properly segregated; and ensure existing MRFs are functional.

observations.recommendation:
In view of the aforementioned observations, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

direct the BAC to submit pertinent documents relative to the (1) creation of the BAC Secretariat and BAC TWG; and (2) policy on the mechanism for identifying/selecting the group from which observers are invited for specific procurements in compliance with the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;

direct the Municipal Engineer to strictly comply with the guidelines on the preparation of the ABC;

strengthen internal control over the evaluation of the bids and post-qualification of bidders by requiring the BAC and the TWG to ensure timeliness, completeness and veracity of the post-qualified documents as reported in the Bid and Post- Qualification Evaluation Reports;

comply strictly with the requirements of R.A. No. 9184 specifically the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 which has become effective last October 28, 2016 in their procurements.

the Municipal Accountant, as the internal auditor, see to it that all the necessary documentary requirements attached to the vouchers are accurate and complete before processing the claim;

the concerned offices submit all the lacking documents to the Audit Team and compliance to pertinent rules and regulations relative to disbursements for infrastructure projects including the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 be strictly implemented to avoid suspension and even disallowance in audit;

the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Engineer explain/justify why time extension was granted despite failure of the contractor to submit its request for time extension prior to August 24, 2016, the revised contract expiry date; and

the concerned officials to comply strictly with Item 6.2, Annex E of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the release of retention money.

Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended that:

the Municipal Accountant:

stop the practice of deducting previous unliquidated cash advances of municipal officials and employees from their subsequent cash advances;

monitor the use of cash advances by the officials and employees;

remind the employees concerned to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period as provided under Section 3.1.2.1 of COA Circular No. 96-004;
ensure that the Liquidation Reports are properly accomplished. 

the Municipal Mayor require the official and employees to refrain from using the cash advances for purposes other than what it is intended for.

We reiterated our recommendation that:

the Municipal Treasurer:

instruct all collectors to prepare RCDs and remit all collections to the Municipal Treasurer in accordance with Section 29, Vol. 1 of the NGAS Manual;
ensure completeness of important information on the face of RCD such as date of the report and date of verification and acknowledgment;
comply with the prescribed format of RCD in accordance with the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
be more strict in the issuance of accountable forms in order to control the delayed remittance of collections; and
refrain from allowing incomplete remittances from the collecting officers.

the Municipal Accountant ensure the accuracy of the amounts of recorded transactions and adjust the balance of the accounts affected by the miscalculated collections.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor require the GAD focal person to strictly monitor if GAD PPAs identified in the DILG-reviewed GAD Plan and Budget during the year are being implemented;

The GAD Focal Point and Council establish and maintain GAD Database through gathering of sex-disaggregated data and GAD-related information to guide them in the planning and implementation of GAD PPAs;

The Sangguniang Bayan formulate and pass a Local GAD Code, or ordinances with the assistance of the LGU GFPS, to support the localization of Magna Carta of Women and to ensure that Gender and Development is mainstreamed in local policy-making and integrated in local development plans; and

The GAD Focal Point Person ensure that all expenditures charged against GAD fund have been properly verified if they relate or correspond to the objective of the programs, projects and activities.

We recommended that Management (a) require the Municipal Local School Board to prepare a balanced budget in compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization; 

(b) refrain from accommodating expenditures on activities/programs for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute; and 

(c) maximize utilization of SEF for the attainment of its primary goals and objectives and ensure that PPAs are in accordance with DepEd criteria and the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund.

We recommended the following courses of action:
Submit written explanation to justify the non-remittance of unspent balance of this account;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to look into the details of the unspent balances pertaining to fund transfers taken up as liability in the Trust Fund books;
Facilitate the remittance to the National Treasury or Source Agency or transfer the said amount to General Fund of the Agency, whichever is appropriate, and make the necessary adjustments in the Trust Fund books immediately; and
Regularly update accounting records particularly on the liabilities account under the Trust Fund books.

We recommended the following courses of action:
Give utmost emphasis on prioritizing the construction of the Sanitary Landfill and Leachate Treatment facility so as to discontinue the use of open dump site as a procedure in solid waste management;
Prepare and submit to this Office the Solid Waste Management Plan and Utilization Reports for the calendar year 2016 and onwards on the prescribe period;
Furnish this Office the resolution that creates the Solid Waste Management Board; and
Enjoin strict adherence to the provisions of the R.A. No. 9003 in the operation and maintenance of the sanitary landfill.

We recommended the following courses of action:
Local Chief Executive should instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to cause the prompt submission to COA Audit Team the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) for all bank accounts maintained by LGU;
Prepare schedules for book errors and make the necessary adjustments within the month it occurred;
Identify the amount of checks matured to stale checks and make the appropriate adjustment; and
Secure copies of Credit and/or Debit Memos from the bank to be attached to the JEVs as supporting documents.

We recommended the following courses of action:
Submit written explanation to justify the occurrence of the said transactions;
Prepare and submit regularly the required monthly reports using the format as prescribed in the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles;
Properly accomplish the prescribed Driver’s Trip Tickets on travels made using government motor vehicles;
Cause the repair of the ODOMETER of government vehicle if this is not functioning, otherwise all purchases of gasoline, oil and lubricants will be disallowed in audit;
Enjoin compliance with COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26 to avoid disallowance in audit due to irregularity of transactions or non-compliance of existing laws, rules and regulations on gasoline/fuel consumption.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Treasurer:
Instruct all collectors to prepare RCDs and remit all collections to the Municipal Treasurer in accordance with Section 29, Vol. 1 of the NGAS Manual;
Ensure completeness of important information on the face of RCD such as date of the report and date of verification and acknowledgment;
Comply with the prescribed format of RCD in accordance with the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
Be more strict in the issuance of accountable forms in order to control the delayed remittance of collections; and
Refrain from allowing incomplete remittances from the collecting officers.

The Municipal Accountant ensure the accuracy of the amounts of recorded transactions and adjust the balance of the accounts affected by the miscalculated collections.

To improve its cash position and financial condition of the municipality the Audit Team recommends the following measures:

1. Officials concerned should comply strictly the provisions of Section 337 of the Local Government Code by limiting disbursements from any local fund up to 50% of the uncollected estimated revenues accruing to such local fund in addition to the actual collections; by intensifying collections on real property taxes, business taxes, especially revenues from income generating projects, to cover any overdraft incurred in the preceding year;

2. Deductions from employees’ payroll which are considered as trust liabilities should be remitted promptly to the government agencies concerned to protect the interest of the employees whose benefits may not be availed of if not remitted on time; 

3. Expenditures on projects funded under Other MOOE accounts should be minimized and prioritized as to what is necessary and essential.

4.  The balance of the LDRRMF for QRF and MOOE shall be transferred to the Trust Fund books pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-002 and be mindful of Section 6.4 of the Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 of National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council, Department of Budget and Management and Department of the Interior and Local Government prescribing that the unexpended LDRRMF shall accrue to a special trust fund solely for the purpose of supporting disaster risk reduction and management activities of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (LDRRMC) within the next five years.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor should:

Ensure that the essential elements in GAD planning are present or strengthened in the Municipality’s GPB;

Direct the GAD Focal Point System and other personnel concerned to strictly adhere to the provisions of Joint Circular No. 2012-01 so that formulation, development, submission, implementation, monitoring, evaluation and accounting of results of the Municipality’s annual GPB and GAD Accomplishment Reports will be in order.
